According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Volume 27, entry for November in the 10th year of {{ill|Emperor Tenji|ja|天智天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} [671 CE]), {{ill|Kanashima Saba|ja|韓嶋裟婆|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and three others reported that {{ill|Tang China|ja|唐|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were preparing to invade Japan.<ref>''Nihon Shoki,'' entry for Emperor Tenji, 10th year, 11th month.</ref>

Following the {{ill|Hayato Rebellion|ja|隼人の反乱|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the 4th year of {{ill|Yōrō|ja|養老|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (720 CE), residents of {{ill|Buzen Province|ja|豊前国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were relocated to {{ill|Ōsumi Province|ja|大隅国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is speculated that the Karashima clan may have a connection to {{ill|Kankoku-uzumine Shrine|ja|韓国宇豆峰神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which enshrines {{ill|Itakeru-no-Mikoto|ja|五十猛命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="inuma" />

During the {{ill|Jingō-keiun|ja|神護景雲|qq=draft|qq=draft}} era (769 CE), during the {{ill|Usa Hachiman Oracle Incident|ja|宇佐八幡宮神託事件|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the priestess {{ill|Karashima no Suguri Yosome|ja|辛嶋勝与曽女|qq=draft|qq=draft}} received an oracle from the Hachiman deity and refused twice to hear the imperial decree read by {{ill|Wake no Kiyomaro|ja|和気清麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the envoy of {{ill|Empress Shōtoku|ja|称徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="inuma" />

