The '''Karashima clan''' (辛嶋氏) was an ancient {{ill|Japanese clans|ja|日本の氏族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese clans|qq=}}. The clan served as shrine families of {{ill|Usa Jingū|lt=Usa Jingū|lt=Usa Shrine|ja|宇佐八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Usa Shrine|qq=}}. The name is also written as '''Karashima''' or '''Kanashima'''. The [[:en:Kabane|kabane]] title was {{ill|Suguri|ja|村主|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suguri|qq=}}.

== Origin ==

The Karashima clan is generally considered to be a {{ill|Toraijin|ja|渡来系氏族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toraijin|qq=}}.<ref name="inuma" /> The genealogical records of the Karashima clan claim descent from {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔嗚尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}} through his son {{ill|Isotakeru-no-Mikoto|lt=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto|lt=Itakeru-no-Mikoto|ja|五十猛神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itakeru-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, further suggesting a migrant origin.<ref name="inuma" />

== Overview ==

The Karashima clan produced female shrine priests ({{ill|negimi|ja|禰宜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/negimi|qq=}}) who served at [[:en:Usa Jingū|Usa Shrine]] during the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]] and [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]]. 

Originally, they served as priests and priestesses at {{ill|Komo Shrine (Oita)|lt=Komo Shrine (Oita)|lt=Komo Shrine|ja|薦神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Komo Shrine|qq=}} (in present-day [[:en:Nakatsu, Ōita|Nakatsu, Ōita]]). After receiving an oracle from the [[:en:Hachiman|Hachiman deity]], they, along with {{ill|Ōgami Hiyoshi|ja|大神比義|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōgami Hiyoshi|qq=}}, established a shrine that became the forerunner of Usa Shrine.

According to the [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]] (Volume 27, entry for November in the 10th year of [[:en:Emperor Tenji|Emperor Tenji]] [671 CE]), {{ill|Kanashima Saba|ja|韓嶋裟婆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanashima Saba|qq=}} and three others reported that [[:en:Tang dynasty|Tang China]] and [[:en:Silla|Silla]] were preparing to invade Japan.<ref>''Nihon Shoki,'' entry for Emperor Tenji, 10th year, 11th month.</ref>

Following the [[:en:Hayato rebellion|Hayato Rebellion]] in the 4th year of [[:en:Yōrō|Yōrō]] (720 CE), residents of [[:en:Buzen Province|Buzen Province]] were relocated to [[:en:Ōsumi Province|Ōsumi Province]]. It is speculated that the Karashima clan may have a connection to {{ill|Kankoku-uzumine Shrine|ja|韓国宇豆峰神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kankoku-uzumine Shrine|qq=}}, which enshrines {{ill|Isotakeru-no-Mikoto|lt=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto|lt=Itakeru-no-Mikoto|ja|五十猛命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itakeru-no-Mikoto|qq=}}.<ref name="inuma" />

During the [[:en:Jingo-keiun|Jingō-keiun]] era (769 CE), during the {{ill|Usa Hachiman Oracle Incident|ja|宇佐八幡宮神託事件|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Usa Hachiman Oracle Incident|qq=}}, the priestess {{ill|Karashima no Suguri Yosome|ja|辛嶋勝与曽女|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karashima no Suguri Yosome|qq=}} received an oracle from the Hachiman deity and refused twice to hear the imperial decree read by [[:en:Wake no Kiyomaro|Wake no Kiyomaro]], the envoy of {{ill|Empress Shōtoku|ja|称徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Shōtoku|qq=}}.<ref name="inuma" />

